# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: internal-developer-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] In software, an **abstraction** provides access while hiding details that otherwise might make access more challenging.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] It focuses attention on details of greater importance.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Examples include the abstract data type which separates use from the representation of data and functions that form a call tree that is more general at the base and more specific towards the leaves.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Computing mostly operates independently of the concrete world.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The hardware implements a model of computation that is interchangeable with others.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The software is structured in architectures to enable humans to create the enormous systems by concentrating on a few issues at a time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] These architectures are made of specific choices of abstractions.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Greenspun's tenth rule is an aphorism on how such an architecture is both inevitable and complex.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Language abstraction is a central form of abstraction in computing: new artificial languages are developed to express specific aspects of a system.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] *Computer languages* can be processed with a computer.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Each stage can be used as a stepping stone for the next stage.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The language abstraction continues for example in scripting languages and domain-specific languages.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Within a programming language, some features let the programmer create new abstractions.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] These include subroutines, modules, polymorphism, and software components.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Some other abstractions such as software design patterns and architectural styles remain invisible to a translator and operate only in the design of a system.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Some abstractions try to limit the range of concepts a programmer needs to be aware of, by completely hiding the abstractions they are built on.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The software engineer and writer Joel Spolsky has criticized these efforts by claiming that all abstractions are *leaky* – that they can never completely hide the details below; however, this does not negate the usefulness of abstraction.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Some abstractions are designed to inter-operate with other abstractions – for example, a programming language may contain a foreign function interface for making calls to the lower-level language.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Different programming languages provide different types of abstraction, depending on the intended applications for the language.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Analysts have developed various methods to formally specify software systems.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Specification languages generally rely on abstractions of one kind or another, since specifications are typically defined earlier in a project, (and at a more abstract level) than an eventual implementation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) specification language, for example, allows the definition of *abstract* classes, which in a waterfall project, remain abstract during the architecture and specification phase of the project.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Programming languages offer control abstraction as one of the main purposes of their use.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Computer machines understand operations at the very low level such as moving some bits from one location of the memory to another location and producing the sum of two sequences of bits.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Programming languages allow this to be done in the higher level.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] To a human, this seems a fairly simple and obvious calculation (*"one plus two is three, times five is fifteen"*).
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] However, the low-level steps necessary to carry out this evaluation, and return the value "15", and then assign that value to the variable "a", are actually quite subtle and complex.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Without control abstraction, a programmer would need to specify *all* the register/binary-level steps each time they simply wanted to add or multiply a couple of numbers and assign the result to a variable.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Structured programming involves the splitting of complex program tasks into smaller pieces with clear flow-control and interfaces between components, with a reduction of the complexity potential for side-effects.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] In a simple program, this may aim to ensure that loops have single or obvious exit points and (where possible) to have single exit points from functions and procedures.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] In a larger system, it may involve breaking down complex tasks into many different modules.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] These layers produce the effect of isolating the implementation details of one component and its assorted internal methods from the others.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Object-oriented programming embraces and extends this concept.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Data abstraction enforces a clear separation between the *abstract* properties of a data type and the *concrete* details of its implementation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The abstract properties are those that are visible to client code that makes use of the data type—the *interface* to the data type—while the concrete implementation is kept entirely private, and indeed can change, for example to incorporate efficiency improvements over time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The idea is that such changes are not supposed to have any impact on client code, since they involve no difference in the abstract behaviour.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] For example, one could define an abstract data type called *lookup table* which uniquely associates *keys* with *values*, and in which values may be retrieved by specifying their corresponding keys.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Such a lookup table may be implemented in various ways: as a hash table, a binary search tree, or even a simple linear list of (key:value) pairs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] As far as client code is concerned, the abstract properties of the type are the same in each case.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Of course, this all relies on getting the details of the interface right in the first place, since any changes there can have major impacts on client code.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] As one way to look at this: the interface forms a *contract* on agreed behaviour between the data type and client code; anything not spelled out in the contract is subject to change without notice.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] While much of data abstraction occurs through computer science and automation, there are times when this process is done manually and without programming intervention.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] One way this can be understood is through data abstraction within the process of conducting a systematic review of the literature.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] In this methodology, data is abstracted by one or several abstractors when conducting a meta-analysis, with errors reduced through dual data abstraction followed by independent checking, known as adjudication.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] In object-oriented programming theory, *abstraction* involves the facility to define objects that represent abstract "actors" that can perform work, report on and change their state, and "communicate" with other objects in the system.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The term encapsulation refers to the hiding of state details, but extending the concept of *data type* from earlier programming languages to associate *behavior* most strongly with the data, and standardizing the way that different data types interact, is the beginning of *abstraction*.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] When abstraction proceeds into the operations defined, enabling objects of different types to be substituted, it is called polymorphism.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] When it proceeds in the opposite direction, inside the types or classes, structuring them to simplify a complex set of relationships, it is called delegation or inheritance.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Various object-oriented programming languages offer similar facilities for abstraction, all to support a general strategy of polymorphism in object-oriented programming, which includes the substitution of one data type for another in the same or similar role.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Although not as generally supported, a configuration or image or package may predetermine a great many of these bindings at compile time, link time, or load time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] This would leave only a minimum of such bindings to change at run-time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Common Lisp Object System or Self, for example, feature less of a class-instance distinction and more use of delegation for polymorphism.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Individual objects and functions are abstracted more flexibly to better fit with a shared functional heritage from Lisp.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] C++ exemplifies another extreme: it relies heavily on templates and overloading and other static bindings at compile-time, which in turn has certain flexibility problems.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Although these examples offer alternate strategies for achieving the same abstraction, they do not fundamentally alter the need to support abstract nouns in code – all programming relies on an ability to abstract verbs as functions, nouns as data structures, and either as processes.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Consider for example a sample Java fragment to represent some common farm "animals" to a level of abstraction suitable to model simple aspects of their hunger and feeding.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] In the above example, the class *`Animal`* is an abstraction used in place of an actual animal, *`LivingThing`* is a further abstraction (in this case a generalisation) of *`Animal`*.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Such an abstraction could remove the need for the application coder to specify the type of food, so they could concentrate instead on the feeding schedule.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The two classes could be related using inheritance or stand alone, and the programmer could define varying degrees of polymorphism between the two types.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] These facilities tend to vary drastically between languages, but in general each can achieve anything that is possible with any of the others.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] A great many operation overloads, data type by data type, can have the same effect at compile-time as any degree of inheritance or other means to achieve polymorphism.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The class notation is simply a coder's convenience.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Decisions regarding what to abstract and what to keep under the control of the coder become the major concern of object-oriented design and domain analysis—actually determining the relevant relationships in the real world is the concern of object-oriented analysis or legacy analysis.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] When discussing formal semantics of programming languages, formal methods or abstract interpretation, *abstraction* refers to the act of considering a less detailed, but safe, definition of the observed program behaviors.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] For instance, one may observe only the final result of program executions instead of considering all the intermediate steps of executions.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Abstraction is defined to a *concrete* (more precise) model of execution.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Abstraction may be *exact* or *faithful* with respect to a property if one can answer a question about the property equally well on the concrete or abstract model.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] For instance, if one wishes to know what the result of the evaluation of a mathematical expression involving only integers +, -, ×, is worth modulo *n*, then one needs only perform all operations modulo *n* (a familiar form of this abstraction is casting out nines).
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Abstractions, however, though not necessarily *exact*, should be *sound*.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] That is, it should be possible to get sound answers from them—even though the abstraction may simply yield a result of undecidability.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The level of abstraction included in a programming language can influence its overall usability.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] The Cognitive dimensions framework includes the concept of *abstraction gradient* in a formalism.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] This framework allows the designer of a programming language to study the trade-offs between abstraction and other characteristics of the design, and how changes in abstraction influence the language usability.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Abstractions can prove useful when dealing with computer programs, because non-trivial properties of computer programs are essentially undecidable (see Rice's theorem).
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Abstraction is the core concept of abstract interpretation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Model checking generally takes place on abstract versions of the studied systems.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Computer science commonly presents *levels* (or, less commonly, *layers*) of abstraction, wherein each level represents a different model of the same information and processes, but with varying amounts of detail.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Each level uses a system of expression involving a unique set of objects and compositions that apply only to a particular domain.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Each relatively abstract, "higher" level builds on a relatively concrete, "lower" level, which tends to provide an increasingly "granular" representation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] For example, gates build on electronic circuits, binary on gates, machine language on binary, programming language on machine language, applications and operating systems on programming languages.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Each level is embodied, but not determined, by the level beneath it, making it a language of description that is somewhat self-contained.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Systems design and business process design can both use this.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Some design processes specifically generate designs that contain various levels of abstraction.
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] Layered architecture partitions the concerns of the application into stacked groups (layers).
[src:internal-developer-platform/abstraction-computer-science] It is a technique used in designing computer software, hardware, and communications in which system or network components are isolated in layers so that changes can be made in one layer without affecting the others.
[src:internal-developer-platform/application-lifecycle-management] ALM is a broader perspective than the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), which is limited to the phases of software development such as requirements, design, coding, testing, configuration, project management, and change management.
[src:internal-developer-platform/application-lifecycle-management] ALM continues after development until the application is no longer used, and may span many SDLCs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/application-lifecycle-management] A research director with research firm Gartner proposed changing the term ALM to ADLM (Application Development Life-cycle Management) to include DevOps, the software engineering culture and practice that aims at unifying software development (Dev) and software operation (Ops).
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:internal-developer-platform/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:internal-developer-platform/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Before the 20th century many businesses such as grocery stores had clerks or assistants who would serve customers individually, taking required items from the shelves, before adding up the total at the till.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Some products such as ham, cheese, and bacon were sliced to order, while dry goods such as flour would be weighed out from large barrels.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] On September 6, 1916 the first Piggly Wiggly opened in Memphis, Tennessee by Clarence Saunders, the world's first self-service grocery store.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Customers would pick up a wicker basket upon entering the store, and then walk through the store placing items they intended to purchase in their baskets.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] As the duties of the shop clerks were reduced to stocking shelves with goods and taking payment at the tills, a "small army of clerks" was no longer necessary, allowing for cost reductions to be passed on to the consumer.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1937, Saunders start opening Keedoozle stores, a further development of his idea of automated grocery stores.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] By the 1950s about 80% of the grocery trade in America was on a self-service basis.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In the United Kingdom, trials with self-service stores began in the Second World War, with the first permanent self-service store, a co-op, opened in 1948, Tesco likewise opened its first self-service store in St Albans later in the same year.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The reduction in the number of staff needed to operate such a store, and the increased speed at which customers could be served, helped to mitigate problems created by the labour shortages in the war.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The concept caught on quickly, with Sainsbury's, Waitrose, Morrisons and Marks & Spencer adopting self-service models in the 1950s, and one sixth of all co-op grocery stores being self-service by 1957.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 2020, Amazon Fresh (a subsidiary of Amazon) opened its first till-less store.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Some of these stores use "grab and go" systems where surveillance cameras and other technology tracks what each customer takes and places back, whereas most use "dash carts" which use touchscreens, barcode scanners, cameras, and various sensors to track items placed into and removed from the cart.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Payment is done by scanning a QR code from their Amazon app, connecting the purchase to their Amazon account and allowing it to be billed through the payment method linked to their account.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1930 the Hoosier Petroleum Co. attempted to trial self-serve fuelling, but was prevented from doing so as it was considered a fire hazard.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1947, Frank Urich opened the first self-service gasoline station in Los Angeles, California.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] It was an unbranded station with rows of self-service pumps and roller-skating attendants who would collect money and reset dispensers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The pumps used mechanical computers to track how much fuel was dispensed, and were manually reset between each customer.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] A few other unbranded stations using this model were created, but the idea didn't catch on with major retailers at the time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1964, Herb Timms showcased an invention to John Roscoe that would allow for an attendant inside the store to dispense gasoline at the pumps.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] This remote fuelling system quickly took off, with three of Roscoe's twelve stores employing it and averaging 4,500 gallons in sales per week.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1961 Britain's first self-service petrol station opened in Southwark, London.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1968, the use of "unattended fuelling" was permitted in the City of London, with BP announcing plans to open self-service units within the city.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] By the mid-1980s, credit card readers were integrated into pump dispensers, allowing for "pay-at-the-pump" transactions.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1998, Japan abolished the Special Petroleum Law, allowing for self-service petrol stations, although at least one attendant is still required to keep watch over customers to ensure safety.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1960, Armenian-American inventor Luther Simjian invented an automated deposit machine (accepting coins, cash and cheques) although it did not have cash dispensing features.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] His US patent was first filed on 30 June 1960 and granted on 26 February 1963.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The roll-out of this machine, called Bankograph, was delayed by a couple of years, due in part to Simjian's Reflectone Electronics Inc. being acquired by Universal Match Corporation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] *The New York Times* wrote in 1998 that it was his most famous invention and "the basis for the now-ubiquitous A.T.M., from which he never made a penny." His device did not see widespread adoption however.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In Europe, in 1967, three independent efforts to create ATMs entered use simultaneously, the Swedish Bankomat, and in the UK the Barclaycash and Chubb MD2.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In 1968 a joint effort between IBM and Swedish banks began testing a networked cashpoint, with Lloyds Bank soon following, deploying networked devices in 1973.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The first vending machine was described in a work by Hero of Alexandria in the 1st century AD.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The machine accepted a coin which when deposited fell upon a pan attached to a lever.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The lever opened a valve which let wine or holy water to flow out.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The pan continued to tilt with the weight of the coin until it fell off, at which point a counterweight snapped the lever back up and turned off the valve after a predetermined amount of liquid was dispensed.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Coin-operated machines that dispensed tobacco were being operated as early as 1615 in the taverns of England.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The machines were portable and made of brass.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] An English bookseller, Richard Carlile, devised a newspaper dispensing machine for the dissemination of banned works in 1822.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Simon Denham was awarded British Patent no.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] 706 for his stamp dispensing machine in 1867, the first fully automatic vending machine.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Vending machines are considerably popular in Japan.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] There are more than 5.5 million machines installed throughout the nation, and Japan holds the highest ratio of machines per person for any country with one machine for every twenty-three people.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Starting in the 19th century, supper, a lighter post-dinner evening meal began to sometimes be served as (and so called) a 'buffet', particularly at larger events such as grand balls.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Likewise large cooked English breakfasts were often served this way.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The term came from the French sideboard which the food was traditionally placed on, before becoming applied to the self-service format of food.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] The all-you-can-eat restaurant was introduced in Las Vegas by Herbert "Herb" Cobb McDonald in 1946.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Various terms have been used to describe end user self service, when someone who is not a professional programmer programs, codes, scripts, writes macros, and in other ways uses a computer in a user-directed data processing accomplishment, such as End user computing and End user development.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In the 1990s, Windows versions of mainframe packages were already available.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] When desktop personal computers became nearly as widely distributed as having a work phone, in companies having a data processing department, the PC was often unlinked to the corporate mainframe, and data was keyed in from printouts.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Software was for do-it-yourself/selfsourcing, including spreadsheets, programs written in DOS-BASIC or, somewhat later, dBASE.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Use of spreadsheets, the most popular End-user development tool, was estimated in 2005 to done by 13 million American employees.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Some data became siloed Once terminal emulation arrived, more data was available, and it was more current.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Techniques such as Screen scraping and FTP reduced rekeying.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Mainframe products such as FOCUS were ported to the PC, and business intelligence (BI) software became more widespread.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Companies large enough to have mainframes and use BI, having departments with analysts and other specialists, have people doing this work full-time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Selfsourcing, in such situations, is taking people away from their main job (such as designing ads, creating surveys, planning advertising campaigns); pairs of people, one from an analysis group and another from a "user" group, is the way the company wants to operate.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Selfsourcing is not viewed as an improvement.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] It is crucial for the system's purposes and goals to be aligned with that of the organizational goals.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Developing a system that contradicts organizational goals will most likely lead to a reduction in sales and customer retention.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] As well, due to the large amount of time it may take for development, it is important allocate your time efficiently as time is valuable.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Knowledge workers must also determine what kind of external support they will require.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] In-house IT specialists can be a valuable commodity and are often included in the planning process.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] It is important to document how the system works, to ensure that if the developing knowledge workers move on others can use it and even attempt to make needed updates.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Knowledge workers are often exactly aware of their immediate needs, and can avoid formalizations and time needed for project cost/benefit analysis and delays due to *chargebacks* or need for managerial/supervisory signoffs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] This eliminates involving a separate IT specialist to cater for what they want.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] There is a greater chance for user short-term satisfaction.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Increased morale can be infectious and lead to benefits in other areas.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Step-by-step details preclude formal documentation, time and resources are concentrated, whereas working with other IT specialists would be less efficient.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Pride of ownership has been found to be a major cause of overlooking errors.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] These incomplete projects, after consuming many hours, often draw workers away from their primary duties.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] These often form a privatized IT system, with poor integration to corporate systems.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Uncontrolled and duplicate information can become stale, leading to more problems than benefits.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Hardware and software opportunities are not analyzed sufficiently, and efficient alternatives may not be noticed and utilized.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] This can lead to inefficient and costly systems.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] End users, as a group, do not understand how to build secure applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Knowledge workers may not have supervisors who are aware that, as time goes on, changes will be needed and these compartmentalized systems will require the help of IT specialists.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Knowledge workers will usually lack experience with planning for these changes and the ability to adapt their work for the future.
[src:internal-developer-platform/self-service] Although departmental computing has decades of history, one-person-show situations either suffer from inability to interact with a helpdesk or fail to benefit from wheels already invented.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS products typically run on rented infrastructure as a service (IaaS) or platform as a service (PaaS) systems including hardware and sometimes operating systems and middleware, to accommodate rapid increases in usage while providing instant and continuous availability to customers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS customers have the abstraction of limitless computing resources, while economy of scale drives down the cost.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS architectures are typically multi-tenant; usually they share resources between clients for efficiency, but sometimes they offer a siloed environment for an additional fee.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Common SaaS revenue models include freemium, subscription, and usage-based fees.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Unlike traditional software, it is rarely possible to buy a perpetual license for a certain version of the software.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] There are no specific software development practices that distinguish SaaS from other application development, although there is often a focus on frequent testing and releases.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) is the most basic form of cloud computing, where infrastructure resources—such as physical computers—are not owned by the user but instead leased from a cloud provider.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] As a result, infrastructure resources can be increased rapidly, instead of waiting weeks for computers to ship and set up.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] IaaS requires time and expertise to make use of the infrastructure in the form of operating systems and applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Platform as a service (PaaS) includes the operating system and middleware, but not the applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS providers typically use PaaS or IaaS services to run their applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Without IaaS, it would be extremely difficult to make an SaaS product scalable for a variable number of users while providing the instant and continual availability that customers expect.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Most end users consume only the SaaS product and do not have to worry about the technical complexity of the physical hardware and operating system.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Because cloud resources can be accessed without any human interactions, SaaS customers are provided with the abstraction of limitless computing resources, while economy of scale drives down the cost.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Another key feature of cloud computing is that software updates can be rolled out and made available to all customers nearly instantaneously.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] In 2019, SaaS was estimated to make up the plurality, 43 percent, of the cloud computing market while IaaS and PaaS combined account for approximately 25 percent.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] In the 1960s, multitasking was invented, enabling mainframe computers to serve multiple users simultaneously.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Over the next decade, timesharing became the main business model for computing, and cluster computing enabled multiple computers to work together.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Cloud computing emerged in the late 1990s with companies like Amazon (1994), Salesforce (1999), and Concur (1993) offering Internet-based applications on a pay-per-use basis.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] All of these focused on a single product to seize a high market share.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Beginning with Gmail in 2004, email services were some of the first SaaS products to be mass-marketed to consumers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The market for SaaS grew rapidly throughout the early twenty-first century.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Initially viewed as a technological innovation, SaaS has come to be perceived more as a business model.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] By 2023, SaaS had become the primary method that companies deliver applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Popular consumer SaaS products include all social media websites, email services like Gmail and its associated Google Docs Editors, Zoom, Dropbox, and entertainment products like Netflix and Spotify.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Enterprise SaaS products include Salesforce's customer relationship management (CRM) software, SAP Cloud Platform, and Oracle Cloud Enterprise Resource Planning.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Some SaaS providers offer free services to consumers that are funded by means such as advertising, affiliate marketing, or selling consumer data.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] One of the most popular models for Internet start-ups and mobile apps is freemium, where the company charges for continued use or a higher level of service.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Even if the user never upgrades to the paid version, it helps the company capture a higher market share and displace customers from a rival.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] However, the company's hosting cost increases with the number of users, regardless of whether it is successful at enticing them to use the paid version.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Another common model is where the free version only provides demonstration (crippleware).
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Online marketplaces may charge a fee on transactions to cover the SaaS provider costs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] It used to be more common for SaaS products to be offered for a one-time cost, but this model is declining in popularity.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] A few SaaS products have open source code, called open SaaS.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This model can provide advantages such as reduced deployment cost, less vendor commitment, and more portable applications.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The most common SaaS revenue models involve subscription and pay for usage.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] For customers, the potential advantages include reduced upfront cost, increased flexibility, and lower overall cost compared to traditional software with perpetual software licenses.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] In some cases, the steep one-time cost demanded by sellers of traditional software were out of the reach of smaller businesses, but pay-per-use SaaS models make the software affordable.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Usage may be charged based on the number of users, transactions, amount of storage spaced used, or other metrics.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Many buyers prefer pay-per-usage because they believe that they are relatively light users of the software, and the seller benefits by reaching occasional users who would otherwise not buy the software.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] However, there are also many buyers who prefer perpetual licenses for reasons such as, high subscription prices, and subscription fatigue.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] It can also cause revenue uncertainty for the seller and increases the overhead for billing.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The subscription model of SaaS offers a continuing and renewable revenue stream to the provider, although vulnerable to cancellation.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] If a significant number are cancelled, the viability of the business can be placed in jeopardy.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The ease of canceling a subscription and switching to a competitor leave customers with the leverage to get concessions from the seller.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] While recurring revenues can help the business and attract investors, the need for customer service skills in convincing the customer to renew their subscription is a challenge for providers switching to subscription from other revenue models.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The Rule of 40 is a commonly used metric by investors to evaluate SaaS company performance, calculated as the sum of revenue growth rate and EBITDA margin (with a target combined score of 40% or above).
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS products are typically accessed via a web browser as a publicly available web application.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This means that customers can access the application anywhere from any device without needing to install or update it.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS providers often try to minimize the difficulty of signing up for the product.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Many capitalize on the service-oriented structure to respond to customer feedback and evolve their product quickly to meet demands.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This can enable customers to believe in the continued improvement of the product and help the SaaS provider get customers from an established traditional software company that likely can offer a deeper feature set.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Although on-premises software is often less secure than SaaS alternatives, security and privacy are among the main reasons cited by companies that do not adopt SaaS products.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS companies have to protect their publicly available offerings from abuse, including denial-of-service attacks and hacking.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] They often use technologies such as access control, authentication, and encryption to protect data confidentiality.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Nevertheless, not all companies trust SaaS providers to keep sensitive data secured.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The vendor is responsible for software updates, including security patches, and for protecting the customers' data.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS systems inherently have a greater latency than software run on-premises due to the time for network packets to be delivered to the cloud facility.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This can be prohibitive for some uses, such as time-sensitive industrial processes or warehousing.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The rise of SaaS products is one factor that has led many companies to shift IT budgets from capital expenditure to operating expenditure.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The process of migration to SaaS and supporting it can also be a significant cost that must be accounted for.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] A challenge for SaaS providers is that demand is not known in advance.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Their system must have enough slack to be able to handle all users without turning any away, but without paying for too many resources that will be unnecessary.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] If resources are static, they are guaranteed to be wasted during non-peak time.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Sometimes cheaper off-peak rates are offered to balance the load and reduce waste.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The expectation for continuous service is so high that outages in SaaS software are often reported in the news.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] There are no specific software development practices that differentiate SaaS from other types of application development.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS products are often released early and often to take advantage of the flexibility of the SaaS delivery model.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Agile software development is commonly used to support this release schedule.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Many SaaS developers use test-driven development, or otherwise emphasize frequent software testing, because of the need to ensure availability of their service and rapid deployment.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Domain-driven design, in which business goals drive development, is popular because SaaS products must sell themselves to the customer by being useful.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS developers do not know in advance which devices customers will try to access the product from—such as a desktop computer, tablet, or smartphone—and supporting a wide range of devices is often an important concern for the front-end development team.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Progressive web applications allow some functionality to be available even if the device is offline.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS applications predominantly offer integration protocols and application programming interfaces (APIs) that operate over a wide area network.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS architecture varies significantly from product to product.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Nevertheless, most SaaS providers offer a multi-tenant architecture.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] With this model, a single version of the application, with a single configuration (hardware, network, operating system), is used for all customers ("tenants").
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This means that the company does not need to support multiple versions and configurations.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The architectural shift from each customer running their own version of the software on their own hardware affects many aspects of the application's design and security features.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] In a multi-tenant architecture, many resources can be used by different tenants or shared between multiple tenants.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The structure of a typical SaaS application can be separated into application and control planes.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS products differ in how these planes are separated, which might be closely integrated or loosely coupled in an event- or message-driven model.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The control plane is in charge of directing the system and covers functionality such as tenant onboarding, billing, and metrics, as well as the system used by the SaaS provider to configure, manage, and operate the service.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Many SaaS products are offered at different levels of service for different prices, called tiering.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This can also affect the architecture for both planes, although it is commonly placed in the control plane.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Unlike the application plane, the services in the control plane are not designed for multitenancy.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The application plane—which varies a great deal depending on the nature of the product—implements the core functionality of the SaaS product.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Key design issues include separating different tenants so they cannot view or change other tenants' data or resources.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Except for the simplest SaaS applications, some microservices and other resources are allocated on a per-tenant basis, rather than shared between all tenants.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Routing functionality is necessary to direct tenant requests to the appropriate services.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Some SaaS products do not share any resources between tenants—called siloing.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Although this negates many of the efficiency benefits of SaaS, it makes it easier to migrate legacy software to SaaS and is sometimes offered as a premium offering at a higher price.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Pooling all resources might make it possible to achieve higher efficiency, but an outage affects all customers so availability must be prioritized to a greater extent.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Many systems use a combination of both approaches, pooling some resources and siloing others.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Other companies group multiple tenants into pods and share resources between them.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] SaaS architecture typically allows users to access applications through a web browser without installing software on their local devices.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] This approach simplifies software maintenance and updates, as service providers can manage the application centrally.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] It also enables organizations to scale services easily according to their needs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] In the United States, constitutional search warrant laws do not protect all forms of dynamically stored SaaS data.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] The result is that governments may be able to request data from SaaS providers without the owner's consent.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] Certain open-source licenses such as GPL-2.0 do not explicitly grant rights permitting distribution as a SaaS product in Germany.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] In 2026, with the emergence of generative AI tools, multiple SaaS companies saw a steep fall in stock market price.
[src:internal-developer-platform/software-as-a-service] February 3 saw a US $300 billion loss of value, in a crisis coined the "SaaS-Pocolypse".
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Internal Developer Platforms are built by platform engineering teams with their end user in mind, the application developers.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Developers are therefore the internal customers of platform teams.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] However, many other stakeholders within the engineering organization need to be involved in the development and rollout of an IDP to ensure adoption.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] These include infrastructure and operations (I&O) teams, architects, security teams, and executives.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] The IDP is designed and shipped in sync with the overall business goals and the objectives of the different stakeholder groups.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Platform teams combine a set of open-source and commercial tools following best-practice architectural blueprints and reference architectures.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Successful platform engineering initiatives start small, following a Minimum Viable Platform (MVP) approach, and iterate quickly to continuously prove value to all key stakeholders.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Enterprise-grade Internal Developer Platforms have a set of baseline configurations that get enforced across all workflows and development teams, driving standardization and automation by design.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] This allows engineering organizations to decrease time to market while ensuring security and compliance best practices are followed everywhere, i.e. they can move faster without breaking things.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Internal Developer Platforms meet application developers where they are at.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Successful platform engineering initiatives provide developers with interface choice (code-based e.g.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] OSS workload specification Score, UI based e.g. a portal, CLI, API, etc.), striking the right balance between shielding them from complexity while still providing them with the context they need to do their job.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Through these interfaces, developers can request resources, spin up fully provisioned environments, roll back, deploy, and trigger deployment automations, all without the need for support from their operations colleagues.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Internal Developer platforms have five core components, reflecting the features and main usage patterns of their different users.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Note, that these are different from the five planes of IDP reference architectures.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Two features are exclusively owned by the platform, Ops, or DevOps or team: *Infrastructure Orchestration* and *Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)*.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] *Application Configuration Management* is used by the platform team to set baseline templates but is also used in day-to-day activity by the application development team.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Developers use the functionalities *Deployment Management* and *Environment Management*.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] All of the above-mentioned building blocks and core components are enabled by the configuration engine at the heart of an IDP, the Platform Orchestrator.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Different interfaces can be plugged on top of the Platform Orchestrator to access the underlying platform capabilities.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] These can be a CLI, different types of User Interfaces (UIs) or developer portals (e.g.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Backstage), or code-based workload specifications (e.g.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Score) It’s important not to get confused by the linguistic similarities between Internal Developer Portals and Internal Developer Platforms.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Portals are simply one of the possible interfaces (UI-based specifically) of the underlying platform.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] IDP should always be used to refer to an Internal Developer Platform, which is the entire platform layer of an enterprise, not a single tool or interface.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Internal Developer Platforms are designed to enable developer self-service on top of complex, brownfield enterprise setups.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] This means an enterprise-grade IDP needs well-established integration patterns with both existing and future tooling.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Top performing platform teams rely on Platform Orchestrators as the glue bringing together the different components of the underlying toolchain.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Orchestrators typically sit post-CI pipeline and ingest built images directly from image repositories.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] They match developers’ requests to the rules and templates defined by the platform team, generating the respective configuration files and handing them over to a CD solution (some orchestrators like Humanitec can also take care of the deployment).
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Monitoring, logging, and security tools can be plugged on top of the orchestrator and across the different workflows of an IDP at the team’s convenience.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] We’ve compiled a long list of all tools we see commonly used within IDPs.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Before we dive into the specifics, let’s briefly look at the reason this category is evolving along with those naming conventions.
[src:internal-developer-platform/what-is-an-internal-developer-platform] Slight variations exist, but we’ve actively decided against those as the descriptions are less accurate and the risk of misunderstanding is too high.
